China has announced that Hamas and Fatah> have held "encouraging" discussions in Beijing > in order to reach the "in-Palestinian reconciliation".><br> After bitter fighting, the Islamist movement Hamas, rival of Fatah of the President of the Palestinian Authority Mahmoud Abbas, took power in 2007 in the Gaza Strip. For more than six months, the Israeli army has been carrying out a major offensive in this area, which has caused the death of many civilians, after the unprecedented attack of Hamas in Israel on 7 October. Fatah maintains partial administrative control in the West Bank, through the Palestinian Authority.
&nbsp;
"At the invitation of China, representatives of the Palestinian National Liberation Movement (Fatah, ndr) and the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas, ndr) recently visited Beijing for deep and frank discussions on the promotion of intra-Palestinian reconciliation," said Lin Jian, spokesman for the Chinese Foreign Ministry. "The two parties fully expressed their political will to achieve reconciliation through dialogue and consultation, discussed many specific issues and made progress," he stressed at a press conference. "They agreed to continue this dialogue process with the aim of reaching the Palestinian unity as quickly as possible," the spokesman added.
&nbsp;
China has been supporting the Palestinian cause for decades. Beijing traditionally fights for a solution based on the principle of the two states, while the Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been stalling since 2014.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
